This folder contains example setups for LaMEM, which is created by Jula scrit.

Using Julia to generate a model setup is a very flexible way to precisely
control the phase and temperature at every point of the domain. You can also look 
at the setup before creating an actual simulation. It generates the input markers,
which are read in by LaMEM upon starting.

Compared to defining the internal geometry, this method has the disadvantage that 
you need to run an Julia script before you start a LaMEM simulation. If the 
resolution of your model domain changes, you'll have to to recreate the input file.

Creating a parallel setup involves 3 steps:

1) Create a partitioning file, by adding the command-line option "-mode save_grid"
    
   Example:
   
   mpiexec -np 8 ../../bin/opt/LaMEM -ParamFile Subduction2D_FreeSlip_Particles_Linear_DirectSolver.dat -mode save_grid
 
2) Run the Julia script and pass partitioning (.bin) file name as an argument:
        
   Example:
    
   julia CreateMarkers_Subduction_Linear_FreeSlip_parallel.jl ProcessorPartitioning_8cpu_4.1.2.bin

   The script will also generate a VTS file of the input geometry and 
   temperature structure, so you can check it is correct, before running a simulation.

3) Run the LaMEM file, the normal way (or with "-mode normal", which is default)
    
   Example:
    
   mpiexec -np 8 ../../bin/opt/LaMEM -ParamFile Subduction2D_FreeSlip_Particles_Linear_DirectSolver.dat

And as always, you can use Paraview to visualize the files.

If you want to run the setup on one processor, you dont't need to generate
the partitioning file. So step 1) falls off, and in step 2 you do need pass the file name.

Input files:

1) Subduction2D_FreeSlip_Particles_Linear_DirectSolver.dat:
   2D subduction setup, in which the slab has a constant (linear) viscosity,
   we employ a free slip upper boundary and a plastic crust.
   Use the Julia script CreateMarkers_Subduction_Linear_FreeSlip_parallel.jl
   to create the input geometry.

